# Save All / Load Project / Reset
1. Save All / Load Project / Reset — not started

This is the complete project save/load system we designed earlier but never built. Nothing from it exists in code yet:

ProjectStateManager class (doesn't exist)
saveProject() — bundle all scene JSONs + referenced assets into a single packaged file (custom extension, internally ZIP)
loadProject() — replace current data/ + relevant assets/ with the unpacked contents; show warning to save first
resetProject() — wipe everything, create a fresh default scene
Menu items for all three under File menu
The custom file extension decision (.ttrpg was proposed but not confirmed)
2. Scene cleanup — known gap (already in our bug list)

SceneController.deleteScene() removes the scene from the in-memory list and scenes.json but leaves data/scenes/{id}.json on disk. This leaks files indefinitely.

Also missing but not in the TODO file:

These came up in design conversations but were never listed in the TODO and were never built:

Log replay window — loadLogFromFile() in MainWindow is a stub; the visual step-through replay with a speed slider was deferred to phase 2
Audio device selection — MusicController has a comment noting this is unimplemented (JavaFX limitation requiring a third-party library)
Browse for music from any location — currently restricted to assets/music/; the general file picker was deferred

# Bugs
1. SceneStateManager.loadMaster() — null activeSceneId propagates silently
If scenes.json exists but activeSceneId is missing/null, manager.getActiveSceneId() returns null. SceneController then calls SceneStateManager.loadScene(null) → scenePath(null) = "data/scenes/null.json" → JsonStateManager.load() returns a fresh empty state with no error.

2. SceneController.addSceneWithId() — new scene file never written until next switch
It calls switchToScene(sceneId) → loadScene(sceneId) → file not found → fresh SceneState returned without ever being saved to disk. If the app crashes before the next mutation, the scene is permanently lost.

3. JsonStateManager.load() always re-saves on every load (line 139)
Every scene switch triggers save(state, filePath) — a full disk write — even when nothing changed. On startup with many scenes, this writes every scene JSON file unnecessarily.

4. JsonStateManager.setFieldDirectly() — reflection on field names that can silently break on rename
"mapImagePath" and "mapWidthInFeet" are string literals. If either field is renamed in SceneState, this silently fails with no compile error. SceneState has public setters for both; a package-private initFromLoad(String mapPath, double feet) method would be both correct and safe.

5. SceneState duplicate Javadoc (lines 130–137) — two /** blocks before findByName.

6. MapController.setNamesVisible() / setStatusVisible() over-refresh
Both call fireStateChanged() which triggers refreshPlayerView() → mapCanvas.syncTokens(). Rebuilding the entire token list when only a visual toggle changed is unnecessary; only mapCanvas.repaint() is needed.

7. LogController.writeEntry() — START_LOG and SCENE_SNAPSHOT pushed into the pointer index
Both events are added to entryOffsets and entryEvents, inflating the lists. minUndoPointer prevents undoing them but they still consume slots and offset the pointer arithmetic.

8. LogParser.parse() loses all timestamps
Every parsed entry gets Instant.now() (parse time), not the original time from the file. Replay will show all entries with the same timestamp.

9. MusicTrack.setVolume() has no bounds check
Values outside [0.0, 1.0] pass directly to MediaPlayer.setVolume(). JavaFX will silently clamp or throw.

10. Entity.xFraction / yFraction setters have no validation
Coordinates outside [0.0, 1.0] place tokens off the canvas with no error.

# OOP violations
11. SceneState.getPlayers(), getCharacters(), getMusicTracks() expose live lists
Callers can mutate them directly without triggering save(). JsonStateManager intentionally uses .add() during load, but this is a wide-open hole for accidental corruption everywhere else.

12. Entity.setId() exists
The comment says the ID is "generated once on creation (used as folder name key)." A public setter contradicts that invariant and is never used.

13. SceneManager.getScenes() returns the live internal list
LogController.writeStartLog() and other callers can add/remove scenes directly, bypassing addScene()/removeScene().

14. SceneManager and SceneState are not final
Every other controller and model class in the project is final. These two are inconsistent.

15. FileHelper.CHARACTERS_DIR, MAPS_DIR, MUSIC_DIR use File.separator
On Windows this gives assets\characters, but stored paths everywhere else use /. SceneController.addEntityToSession() already works around this with FileHelper.CHARACTERS_DIR + "/" + name, creating a mixed-separator string. avatarPathFor() and detailsPathFor() also use File.separator and are effectively never used as a result (dead utility methods).

16. LogWriter duplicates the parsing logic of LogParser
LogWriter.parseSingle() and LogParser.parse() parse the same text format with two independent implementations. A format change requires updating both.

17. SidebarPanel mixes UI with logic
assignDisplayName() (numbering algorithm) and promptForSize() (entity sizing input) are domain/input logic living in a UI panel class. They should be in a service or controller.

18. MainWindow.wireScenePanel() and MainWindow.loadLogFromFile() use inline FQN
ttrpgdash.scene.SceneEntry::getName, javafx.stage.FileChooser, and java.io.File appear as inline FQNs instead of imports, inconsistent with the rest of the file and will trigger checkstyle.

19. TokenLayer callback fields use inline FQN
java.util.function.Consumer<Token> and java.util.function.BiConsumer<Token, double[]> written inline instead of via imports — same checkstyle concern.

20. MapController is not final
All other controllers are final.